Its a bit confusing but actually really useful. 

So actually, the registers of our cpu can take multiple jobs, depending on the instruction 
In our case we are executing a system exit. how it work is we do something called a 
mov (move) instruction. it takes in a static number and puts it in the register

So whats the deal? why do we need eax, ebx here even though EBX is G.P. and eax is for math?
We use them because they can take multiple jobs. 
We typed in something called an 'interrupt' by using 80h (hexadecimal)
When our compiler saw that it immediatly changed the job of eax, ebx 

EAX now takes job as a Room Number, or in official terms the \\System Call Number\\
    Basically in simple terms, in the linux kernel the rule of a SysCalls ID
    is that every task is used with a number
    so for example, there are rooms for Exit, Write, Read, Open
EBX now takes place as the Paperwork, or in official terms the \\Arguments\\
    Basically its like what we pass into Syscalls ID to get some kind of result
    Arguments are used in asm-in instructions to get some kind of result they need.
        (Example below)
    BUT!!! IN our case EBX only takes the role of a 'result' 
    so for example when we do return 0; in C it means that the program executed succesfully.
    Its practically the same thing here.

        NOTE: EBX is not only the argument in asm, theres also 2 more, here they are in order;
            1. EBX 2. ECX 3. EDX
            Why: for example if you needed to access the Write office, you would need 3 args
            EAX = 4 [sys_write]; EBX = 1 [stdout]; ECX = msg; EDX = 13[amm. of bytes in msg]
INT 80h is just used to get a result value if executed succefully
    Almost always the result of the program is put back into the EAX register